<paragraph id="1E2E36E96162F550FCB3D2C2FBC5FC05" blockId="1.[799,1100,941,963]" box="[799,1100,941,963]" pageId="1" pageNumber="113">
<heading id="456681856162F550FCB3D2C2FBC5FC05" box="[799,1100,941,963]" centered="true" fontSize="9" level="2" pageId="1" pageNumber="113" reason="2">
<taxonomicName id="D9914D6A6162F550FCB3D2C2FBC5FC05" authority="Champion, 1906" authorityName="CHAMPION" authorityYear="1906" box="[799,1100,941,963]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Microzygops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="113" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2CE5EAFB6162F550FCB3D2C2FBC5FC05" bold="true" box="[799,1100,941,963]" pageId="1" pageNumber="113">
<emphasis id="2CE5EAFB6162F550FCB3D2C2FC15FC04" bold="true" box="[799,924,941,963]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="113">Microzygops</emphasis>
Champion, 1906
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1E2E36E96162F550FD77D2B7FB84FA77" blockId="1.[707,1194,984,1456]" pageId="1" pageNumber="113">
Champion based his genus on the following combination of characters: “very long, slender legs, unarmed posterior femora, exserted head, cylindrical constricted prothorax, large eyes, deeply excavate anterior portion of the metasternum, &amp;c.” (see also 
<bibRefCitation id="7A004B186162F550FCB7D533FC2CFBB6" author="Anzaldo, S. S." box="[795,933,1116,1137]" pageId="1" pageNumber="113" pagination="51 - 138" refId="ref3408" refString="Anzaldo, S. S. 2017. Review of the genera of Conoderinae (Coleoptera, Curculionidae) from North America, Central America, and the Caribbean. ZooKeys 683: 51 - 138. DOI: 10.3897 / zookeys. 683.12080." type="journal article" year="2017">Anzaldo 2017</bibRefCitation>
). The character of unarmed metafemora is variable, with some individuals possessing a short, acute tooth, some with only a tiny bump, and some lacking a tooth altogether. Variation also occurs in size and basic coloration. Although long, slender legs, unarmed metafemora, and an excavate metasternum are found in other conoderine genera, notably 
<taxonomicName id="D9914D6A6162F550FC66D479FCA2FA81" authority="Champion, 1906" authorityName="Champion" authorityYear="1906" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Pseudolechriops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="113" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2CE5EAFB6162F550FC66D479FBE8FAEB" box="[970,1121,1302,1324]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="113">Pseudolechriops</emphasis>
Champion, 1906
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="7A004B186162F550FC91D45EFBFEFA81" author="Hespenheide, H. A. &amp; L. M. LaPierre" box="[829,1143,1329,1350]" pageId="1" pageNumber="113" pagination="1 - 39" refId="ref3613" refString="Hespenheide, H. A., and L. M. LaPierre. 2006. A review of Pseudolechriops (Coleoptera: Curculionidae: Conoderinae). Zootaxa 1384: 1 - 39." type="journal article" year="2006">Hespenheide and LaPierre 2006</bibRefCitation>
), the combination of all these characters produces an unusual overall habitus. 
<taxonomicName id="D9914D6A6162F550FC3FD409FB81FABC" authorityName="CHAMPION" authorityYear="1906" box="[915,1032,1382,1403]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Microzygops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="113" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2CE5EAFB6162F550FC3FD409FB81FABC" box="[915,1032,1382,1403]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="113">Microzygops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not obviously closely related to any other conoderine genus, and its relationships await genetic analysis.
</paragraph>
